Clan Brujah is largely composed of rebels, both with and without causes. Individualistic, outspoken and turbulent, Brujah hold social change near to their undead hearts, and the clan's ranks contain some of the most violent of the Camarilla Kindred. Most other vampires perceive the Brujah as nothing more than punks and miscreants, but the truth of the matter is that genuine passion lies behind their polemics.
The Brujah Clan Symbol BrujahA.gif

Brujah Kindred adopt pet passions and causes, which they support with volume and vitriol. Some brujah follow charismatic members of their clan, while others prefer stances of blatant, defiant individualism. The clan claims a history rich with warrior-poets, and it has adapted this concept into the modern night; many Brujah are glad to have an opportunity to speak their minds, then indulge in a bit of destruction afterwards to illustrate their points. The Rabble's espousal of change unites them, albeit tenuously, in their nightly crusades. Given a common enemy, Brujah with vastly differing ideals will join side by side to oppose their foe. After that foe is defeated, however, all bets are off and it's back to business as usual. A common Brujah theme involves the foundation of a Kindred "Utopia," or the re-creation of a mythical one from nights past, though each Brujah vampire has a different idea of what said Utopia is.

Brujah rely on chaotic behavior and upheaval to get their ideas across, and the Rabble are allowed a certain leeway that other clans do not have. In fact, Brujah are almost expected to be incoherent and bellicose; this stereotype works to the advantage of many eloquent, well-spoken members of the clan, who have no need to resort to violence when making their arguments.

Respected for their martialry and readiness to rally under a banner, the Brujah are the phyisical strength of the Camarilla. Of late, however, many Rabble neonates see their role in the Camarilla as an institution unto itself, and more than a little unrest circulates among the clan.

Introduced in 1990, the Colt Anaconda is a large frame double-action revolver featuring a full length under-barrel ejection-rod lug and six round cylinder, designed and produced by the Colt's Manufacturing Company. Chambered for the powerful .44 Magnum and .45 Colt centerfire ammunition cartridges, the Anaconda marked the Hartford, Connecticut firm's first foray into the popular large-bore Magnum pistol market.

Due to its high quality of manufacture, the Anaconda is is considered to have lethal stopping power. As such, it grants a bonus 1 to 4 damage on critical hits.

A baseball bat is a smooth wooden club used in the game of baseball to hit the ball after the ball is thrown by the pitcher. A bat may also be used as a club-like weapon. Baseball bats are often associated with crime and assault in the public mind, and rightfully so. Cheap, heavy, and sturdy, the bat makes an excellent blunt weapon.

Winchester Model 1894 (also known as Winchester .30-30 rifle, Winchester 94, Win 94, .30-30 Winchester, or simply .30-30) is one of the most famous and most popular hunting rifles. It was designed by John Browning in 1894, and was produced by Winchester Repeating Arms Company through 1980 and then by U.S. Repeating Arms under the Winchester brand until they ceased to manufacture rifles in 2006.

The Winchester Model 94 Big Bore is a lever-action rifle typical of big-bore hunting rifles found around the world.

The AKS-74U short assault rifle (the "U" suffix means "Ukorochennyj" in Russian = "Shortened" in English) has been developed in the late 1970s from the AKS-74 assault rifle. The AKS-74U was intended as a personal defense weapon for tanks, guns, helicopters and other vehicles crews, and for the special operations forces, who required a compact but relatively powerful individual automatic weapon. The AKS-74U has the size and effective range of a typical submachine gun, but has advantage of the general issue, assault rifle ammunition and magazines, as well as the parts interchangeability with the general issue assault rifle, the AK-74. Since its introduction the AKS-74U, unofficially known as a "Ksyukha" (variation of a Russian woman name) or "okurok" (cigarette stub), also had been issued to various Police and other Law Enforcement forces acres the USSR and the Post-USSR countries, including Russia. Interestingly, the AKS-74U is known in the USA as the "Krinkov", but what it means is a mystery for me. The AKS-74U is somewhat popular among its users due to its compact size, which allows it to be carried in the cars and even concealed under the clothes. On the other side, its effective range of fire is greatly limited by the poor accuracy at extended ranges, while the bullet itself remains its lethality at much greater ranges. The AKS-74U also known for its tendency for rapid overheating during the prolonged fire sessions. A special version of the AKS-74U had been developed for the Special Forces (SpetsNaz), which could be fitted with quickly detachable silencer and a special 30mm silenced grenade launcher model BS-1 "Tishina" ("silence"). The launcher uses special HE-DP grenades, which are launched using special blank cartridges, stored in the box magazine, contained in the launcher pistol grip. The 45-round plastic magazine of the RPK-74 light machine gun is also interchangeable with that of the AK-74.

What? Rules?!? Yup, we have them because we're humans and we all need guidelines with how to behave.)

- Must be 18 years of age or older to join.
- Don't be a butt. Seriously. We're all adults here.
- The DMs have final say. They will settle the arguments and their decision is what will be canon.
- PvP only with permission. Any serious IC injuries or mistreatment must have verifiable OOC permission.
- Character deaths are only permanent when either the player wants to kill them off or the DMs say so. A DM must witness the death, as well.
- Keep in-character and out-of-character separate.
- No meta-gaming/god-gaming. No exploiting.
- If you want to ERP (erotic roleplay), take it somewhere private and use whispers or tells.
- Items and/or gold are not transferable between characters except under certain circumstances (bequeath to a spouse, child, or clan member).
- Characters must be unique. If you rip off a character idea from any source other than your own noggin', it will be denied. A second offense results in banishment.
- If a DM is on as a character, do not bother them about DM-related issues in the game. They want to play, too. Ask in the appropriate Discord text channel, instead.
-If an RP is going to be triggering (excessive violence, gore, etc), OOC permission must be obtained by all involved. Warning should be given to any within proximity and the RP should take place via tells or whispers only.
- No pick-pocketing or stealing special items from other players unless for RP purposes with OOC permission given.

2)standard races, or a subrace from the WhiteWolf campaign setting. (Garou, Vampire, Human hunters, Kinfolk(no support for), Ghouls (no support for), or humans) No demons, magi, devils, Wraths, other changing breeds are allowed with out DM permission.

3) Name your pc a Reasonible name.
	a) you can add florishes if you like

	a) it will detrimine a general guildline how your pc will act.
	b) it is a Evil alignments also represent how tainted or/and corrupt your pcs is. not all alignments are allowed in every faction.

5) When taking a class you are expected to have rp ways to explain your skills and powers you have gained.
	a) meaning that if you choose to take Red Dragon Disiple or Pale Master do not expect to have the wings or arm letoed out. Only through rping with said deformity and a dm involved (via pc or npc) in having them removed  or fixed will earn them being letoed out.

6) All prestige classes are required to have a minium of three levels by the time you reach the server max level those found with out will be deleveled to have their pc fixed to meet with this rule.

On Player vs. Player: 

Player vs. Player (PvP) conflict is allowed and will very likely occur due to the highly conflictive state of the world. Please Expect that when playing here.

-Firstly, we are all here to have fun. Very often PvP actions are only fun for one side. PvP should be enjoyable for all that are involved, should stay 100% IC and never be brought on by OOC conflicts. Any PvP conflict should put the players enjoyment first. 
        
 ******ALL PVP battles require either IC warning (ie *pulls out blade* Your evil deed shall end here " wait for some ic response such as "you dont have the grapes to do it") OR an ooc warning in the form of a tell or setting to hostile. 

 One liners dont count as rps around pvp battles, send a tell. Those that receive the tell be realistic and do not metagame this knowledge. Time limits must be followed as pre the rest of these  rules .******

- When a person is winded, knocked out, or ect. the conflict is over. There is to be no more pvp between the two parties for a minium of 10 minutes. In real life if you have the crap kicked out of you your not going to get up and be able to attack again.

-Next, if a PvP situation ends in a characters death  that situation is resolved, neither character should take any further action towards each other due to those happenings (a.k.a. no hunting for revenge) for at least 24 real hours ( exception is an agreement between parties and no complaining to staff about it if you agree). After this time limit has been reached, a PC may seek revenge so long as it is in line with these rules. A tell must be sent to the player to do this. It is also in this area that trying to premakill a pc is under for all cases a player must agree to the permadeath of their pc by another pc, unless it leads to last life stone the person has. ALL other cases of premakilling a pc MUST be DM directed or involved.

It is strongly suggested that if a PK (Player Kill) is intended, that the player notify the other player of his intentions through a tell beforehand. Also use common sense when getting into pvps while it might make RP sense for your level 35 pc to kill the new level 2 vampire find a way around it such as emote beating them down or something along those lines.

On Pick Pocketing and Stealing:

Players are allowed to pick pocket from each other there is a limit to what how often you can pick pocket from someone being limited to once every 5 minutes unless you have talked with said target before hand based on RP reasoning with your character.

People work hard to get the items they have and stealing items from them makes the game less fun for others. Please help in this by following this rule to make the server more enjoyible.

On Metagaming: 

What is metagaming: Metagaming simply put is using OOC information as IC information. There are many forms of Metagaming, and we have a general all encompassing rule to deal with it. 

Metagaming is bad when used to gain some form of in-game advantage (i.e. Using OOC knowledge to hunt down a character in PvP situations). 

Metagaming is good when it helps add enjoyment to the game (for everyone involved) (i.e. asking a friend in tells where they are and arranging to "run into each other" and go adventuring).

On Items: 

 If you find an item you may use it or sell it as you choose. We would appreciate if you would mention it to a DM if you find an item that seems overly powerful for your level. 

Gifting items to other players is not encouraged but allowed if there is good IC reasons for the gift. If you are unsure if an item is appropriate feel free to make an inquiry to a DM.

Vampires

On Ghouling- To make a Ghoul it Requires three drinks from the vampire to make over three nights in a one month period. The ghouling process starts as soon as drink one is taken and the pc will stop aging at drink one. The effects are as follows; Drink one The ghoul will now have an unconscious desire to stumble into their regent (aka vampire) the bond created is very easily broken should the person find out they are becoming addicted to the vampires blood (DC 20 will save not to drink more). Drink two means the person will consciously Regent and feelings of loyality begin to form this level is harder to break and it becomes difficult to resist drinking of the Regent's blood (bond can still be broken to resist drinking the blood via DC25 will save). Third drink you become completely addicted to the Regents blood making it extremely hard to not drink from them any time it is offered. You have feelings of loyality and will find it very difficult to harm your Regent to do so you would have to make a will save of dc 40 to temporarily safe off the bonds effects. While saying this you are not a complete slave to your Regent's will you have free will and can act on your own so long as it does not bring harm to the Regent but your addiction is like that of a crack additic you will always want to keep coming back for more until the addiction has pasted takes one year of saves to make, but you can drop that back down to the level one for that year but making checks to not drink from your Regent while close. After not having had a drink of your Regent's Blood will make life difficult for you as you willdraw for a long period of time. Making decisions and focusing on things will become very difficult (ie weakness of the limbs, dizziness, headache, tembling etc), as well as the gnawing need for that blood your body wants. Fort save can hold off this effect for 24 hours saves same as above for will. Note Garou can not be ghouled should you feed blood to a garou they will vomit the blood up violently then likely come hunting for you.

Blood Bond- Is the same as above but it is much harder to break and between two vampires. Every drink after the third drink will up the difficulty of a will save by 1. The vampire is subject to the whims and will of their Regent they end up being granted as much or as little freewill as the Regent allows. Time for this 3rd level bond to slip down to a lower level is 1 year from last drink. Then to drop it back down from a level 2 bond takes another 6 months, and level 1 will take one month to completely break said bond. Person must make will checks DC 40+ number of drinks to not drink the Regents blood when offered or to go against the Regent's wishes or harm them.

The Beretta 92 pistols were developed by the italian company Armi Pietro Beretta Spa. Original pistol, Beretta 92, entered production in 1976 and was based on early Beretta pistol, model 1951. Model 92 was adopted by Italian army and also manufactured under licence in Egypt. Later, the model 92 became the subject for many modifications that are listed below. 

Beretta 92S - Model 92 with modified safety: frame mounted safety was replaced by slide mounted hammer drop safety/decocker lever. In all other aspects the model 92S is similar to early model 92. Model 92S has been used by Italian Army and police, as well as by other forces. No longer in production.

Beretta 92F - also known as model 92SB-F. Developed in 1983, this model is a further modification of the model 92SB, that featured slightly re-shaped grip, plastic grip panels and new, more durable finish.

The Glock family of pistols, once started by famous Glock 17 pistol, was developed by Austrian company Glock Gmbh., previously known for quality knives and entrenching tools. The Glock 17 pistol first appeared at the Austrian Army trials, won it and was adopted by Austrai Army and Police in the early 1980s under the designation of P-80. Since then, the Glock 17 and its descentants become very popular military and law enforcement firearms, being exported in more than 50 countries. Currently, Glocks are chambered in all major pistol calibers, namely 9x17mm Short (.380ACP), 9x19mm Luger, .357SIG, .40SW, 10mm auto and .45ACP. Also, Glocks available in full-size service models, semi-compact models, compact models for concealed/backup carry, and in longslide competition models. Training versions, firing non-lethal practice ammo, also available. 

Due to its high quality of manufacture, the Glock 17 is always considered a mastercraft weapon. As such, it grants a +1 bonus on attack rolls.

The British company Webley and Scott (P. Webley & Son before merger with W & C Scott) produced a range of revolvers from the late 19th to late 20th centuries. Early models such as the Webley-Green army model 1879 and the Webley-Pryse model were first made during the 1870s.

The best-known are the range of military revolvers, which were in service use across two World Wars and numerous colonial conflicts, but Webley & Scott also produced a number of short-barrel solid-frame revolvers, including the Webley RIC (Royal Irish Constabulary) model and the British Bulldog revolver, designed to be carried in a coat pocket for self-defence.
